'''Maria Grey Training College''' was a [[Teacher training college|training college]] for female  teachers from [[1878]]-[[1976]].

==History==
The college was opened as the '''Teachers<U+2019> Training & Registration Society College''' on 1 May 1878 in the Clergy House, Skinner Street, [[Bishopsgate]] (now Pindar Street). The Teachers<U+2019> Training & Registration Society was created by the Women's Education Union to promote women<U+2019>s right to education and the professional recognition of female teachers.<ref name ='Maria Grey Collection'>{{cite web
| last = Brunel University
| title = Maria Grey Collection
| url = http://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/administration/infoaccess/archives/collections/mariagrey
| accessdate = 2008-12-12}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  The Society was promoted by [[Maria Georgina Grey]] who had also been fundamental in the founding of the Union. In 1885 it moved to Fitzroy Square,<ref>{{citation | title=Women, scholarship and criticism: gender and knowledge, c.1790-1900 | first1=Anne | last1=Laurence| first2=Joan | last2=Bellamy | first3=Gillian | last3= Perry | publisher = Manchester University Press | year=2000 | isbn=9780719057205 | 
url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yInCeozo9pQC&pg=PA103 | page=103}}</ref> and in March 1886 it was renamed '''Maria Grey College''' after its founder.<ref name='Maria Grey Collection'/> In 1946 it moved to [[Twickenham]]. In 1976 the College merged with [[Borough Road College]] and [[Acton & Chiswick Polytechnic]] to form the [[West London Institute of Higher Education]].<ref name='Maria Grey Collection'/> In 1995 the West London Institute of Higher Education became part of [[Brunel University]].<ref>{{cite web
| last = Brunel University
| title = 'History'
| url = http://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/history
| accessdate = 2008-12-12}}</ref>. The site was sold when the department moved to [[Uxbridge]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite web
| last = Brunel University
| title = 'Maria Grey'
| url = http://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/history/mg
| accessdate = 2009-02-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

==Primary sources==
The records of the College are now held in the Brunel University Archives.<ref>{{cite web
| last = Brunel University
| title = University Collections
| url = http://www.brunel.ac.uk/about/administration/infoaccess/archives/collections
| accessdate = 2008-12-12}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

